      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me with this python function? its for my uni tech comp sci lab and the automated grader keeps failing me cuz it says \"time limit exceeded.\" i need to optimize the time complexity so it passes the big test cases (n > 10^7) or i'm gonna lose points. basically just make it fast enough to pass.\n\nhere is the code:\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        count = 0\n        for j in range(1, i + 1):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                count += 1\n        results.append(count)\n    return sum(results)\n\nhow do i make this run fast enough so the grader doesn't time out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue here is that your function has a time complexity of O(n^2) due to the nested loops. For large inputs, this can lead to timeouts. \n\nOne optimization you can make is to use a mathematical formula to calculate the count of divisors instead of iterating over all numbers up to `i`. The count of divisors of a number `i` is equal to the product of the exponents of its prime factors. \n\nHere's an optimized version of your function:\n\n```python\ndef prime_factors(n):\n    factors = {}\n    i = 2\n    while i * i <= n:\n        if n % i:\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            n //= i\n            factors[i] = factors.get(i, 0) + 1\n    if n > 1:\n        factors[n] = factors.get(n, 0) + 1\n    return factors\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        factors = prime_factors(i)\n        count = 1\n        for factor in factors.values():\n            count *= (factor + 1)\n        results.append(count)\n    return sum(results)\n```",
      "source": "target",
